So there was one rule
that was inviolate--

00:40:07.680 --> 00:40:09.730
if you want to be a member
of the group you had

00:40:09.730 --> 00:40:12.140
to buy the book, which
was very nice of her.

00:40:12.140 --> 00:40:13.910
And then the second
rule she came up

00:40:13.910 --> 00:40:17.950
with had to do with
distributing your recipes, which

00:40:17.950 --> 00:40:20.930
was the only person who
could do the recipe online

00:40:20.930 --> 00:40:24.120
was the person who chose
the recipe for that week.

00:40:24.120 --> 00:40:26.800
So that just-- all the
recipes were still out there,

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:28.960
but they weren't out
there in the thousands.

00:40:28.960 --> 00:40:31.990
So it just was a nice
gesture on her part

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:34.290
towards the author,
which is really great.

00:40:34.290 --> 00:40:35.790
DORIE GREENSPAN:
It's a great group.

00:40:35.790 --> 00:40:40.970
When I spoke at on the
International Food Bloggers

00:40:40.970 --> 00:40:43.130
Conference, and
about 20 people who

00:40:43.130 --> 00:40:46.650
are members of TWD
and FFWD-- Tuesdays

00:40:46.650 --> 00:40:48.440
with Dorie and French
Fridays with Dorie--

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:50.140
came to the conference,
so we actually

00:40:50.140 --> 00:40:53.900
got to meet one another and
they got to meet one another.

00:40:53.900 --> 00:40:56.480
But they already-- they'd
never seen one another

00:40:56.480 --> 00:40:58.270
face to face but
they really knew one

00:40:58.270 --> 00:41:01.070
another from being
part of this group.

00:41:01.070 --> 00:41:03.960
And in fact, Lori
went to Seattle

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:08.470
to be the matron of honor
at the wedding of a Tuesdays

00:41:08.470 --> 00:41:12.330
with Dorie member and
they had never met.

00:41:12.330 --> 00:41:15.600
They only knew one
another through baking.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:18.420
I just think it's fabulous.

00:41:18.420 --> 00:41:20.280
AUDIENCE: A two parter question.

00:41:20.280 --> 00:41:25.110
So the first part
is at your house,

00:41:25.110 --> 00:41:27.360
when you're in France,
what do you cook when you

00:41:27.360 --> 00:41:30.890
invite your French friends over?

00:41:30.890 --> 00:41:33.700
And the second part is have
do you ever thought, gee

00:41:33.700 --> 00:41:35.940
this would be wonderful,
they'll really love it,

00:41:35.940 --> 00:41:37.580
and then not so much?

00:41:37.580 --> 00:41:40.250
Like just their
French taste didn't

00:41:40.250 --> 00:41:42.509
quite jive with
your American taste?

00:41:42.509 --> 00:41:43.550
DORIE GREENSPAN: Oh wait.

00:41:43.550 --> 00:41:44.955
OK, so that's an
interesting question.

00:41:44.955 --> 00:41:46.530
And I was going to say,
I don't know the answer,

00:41:46.530 --> 00:41:47.750
but Michael knows the answer.

00:41:47.750 --> 00:41:48.585
MICHAEL GREENSPAN: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:48.585 --> 00:41:49.475
DORIE GREENSPAN: Yeah.

00:41:49.475 --> 00:41:51.260
MICHAEL GREENSPAN: Um,
when I was growing up--

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:52.926
DORIE GREENSPAN: Oh,
I know exactly what

00:41:52.926 --> 00:41:54.370
you're going to say, yeah.

00:41:54.370 --> 00:41:55.910
I know.

00:41:55.910 --> 00:41:56.780
Yeah, untouched.

00:41:56.780 --> 00:42:01.170
Potato nik is not
a French favorite.

00:42:01.170 --> 00:42:05.370
Do you know I cook-- when my
French friends come to dinner,

00:42:05.370 --> 00:42:09.400
I cook-- sometimes I cook
very traditional French food,

00:42:09.400 --> 00:42:15.400
sometimes we'll fry chicken
or we'll make hamburgers,

00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:19.210
or we'll do something
very American.

00:42:19.210 --> 00:42:22.912
The French are-- I was
going to say adventurous

00:42:22.912 --> 00:42:24.620
and I'm wondering now
that I'm saying it,

00:42:24.620 --> 00:42:26.036
are they adventurous
or forgiving?

00:42:30.170 --> 00:42:34.140
They're usually really happy
to have anything that I make

00:42:34.140 --> 00:42:35.520
and they're very appreciative.

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:37.140
Some of them are just surprised.

00:42:37.140 --> 00:42:40.330
I mean somebody
said to me, oh, you

00:42:40.330 --> 00:42:43.650
know how to make a vinaigrette.

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:46.160
I though, yeah, I know how
to make a vinaigrette, right.

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:53.310
I think that there's some amount
of surprise that Americans cook

00:42:53.310 --> 00:42:58.360
and eat well, that there's
this idea that-- I mean,

00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:03.120
it's-- we are a nation of
hamburger eaters to many people

00:43:03.120 --> 00:43:05.400
outside of our country.

00:43:05.400 --> 00:43:08.840
But I cook all sorts
of things, and the food

00:43:08.840 --> 00:43:11.240
that's in "Around
my French Table"

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:13.420
really comes from
the food that I've

00:43:13.420 --> 00:43:17.827
cooked for friends
around my French table.

00:43:17.827 --> 00:43:20.160
I'm trying to think if there's
anything else that I ever

00:43:20.160 --> 00:43:22.512
did that they didn't like.

00:43:22.512 --> 00:43:23.220
I don't think so.

00:43:23.220 --> 00:43:26.440
The potato nik was
just-- went over

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:29.579
like a heavy potato pudding.

00:43:29.579 --> 00:43:30.370
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:43:30.370 --> 00:43:30.470
DORIE GREENSPAN: Hi.

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:31.540
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:31.540 --> 00:43:34.366
I'm headed to Paris this
summer for the first time--

00:43:34.366 --> 00:43:35.490
DORIE GREENSPAN: Lucky you.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:38.100
AUDIENCE: --and we are
very, very excited.

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:40.600
My boyfriend's lived
there for some time,

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:41.680
but it's my first time.

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:42.630
And I'm curious.

00:43:42.630 --> 00:43:44.100
I've heard a lot
of mixed reviews

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:48.770
about trying to speak
French with the French.

00:43:48.770 --> 00:43:51.650
What's the best way to
not be hated, especially--

00:43:51.650 --> 00:43:52.840
DORIE GREENSPAN: Smile.

00:43:52.840 --> 00:43:53.565
Smile.

00:43:53.565 --> 00:43:54.440
AUDIENCE: Just smile.

00:43:54.440 --> 00:43:55.606
DORIE GREENSPAN: Just smile.

00:43:55.606 --> 00:43:58.082
All you have to do is smile.

00:43:58.082 --> 00:43:58.790
It's interesting.

00:43:58.790 --> 00:44:02.280
Sometimes if you
try to speak French

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:06.010
and your French isn't
good, a French person

00:44:06.010 --> 00:44:09.070
might answer you in English
if he or she can do that.

00:44:09.070 --> 00:44:11.990
And when I was younger,
I used to think,

00:44:11.990 --> 00:44:14.400
how dare you-- is my
French that bad that you

00:44:14.400 --> 00:44:15.580
won't listen to it?

00:44:15.580 --> 00:44:17.915
But I think they're
really just being helpful.

00:44:17.915 --> 00:44:19.290
They want to make
it easy for you

00:44:19.290 --> 00:44:22.560
to be able to be understood
and get what you want.

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:26.490
And if you say to a
French person, oh,

00:44:26.490 --> 00:44:30.790
I want to speak French,
I have to practice--

00:44:30.790 --> 00:44:35.000
[SPEAKING FRENCH]--
they'll speak with you.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.690
But it's interesting--
when we first

00:44:37.690 --> 00:44:41.910
started to go to France it was
very hard to find people who

00:44:41.910 --> 00:44:44.620
spoke English or wanted
to speak English.

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:48.660
Now so many people do,
and they really want to.

00:44:48.660 --> 00:44:52.260
We have friends who work
for French companies

00:44:52.260 --> 00:44:54.980
but all of their
meetings are in English.

00:44:54.980 --> 00:44:59.690
It's really become the language.

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:01.020
So just smile.

00:45:01.020 --> 00:45:02.997
As long as you smile.

00:45:02.997 --> 00:45:06.910
You have a cute
smile, you'll be fine.

00:45:06.910 --> 00:45:09.010
AUDIENCE: I have a follow-up.

00:45:09.010 --> 00:45:11.420
So obviously, your
cookbooks are a great start

00:45:11.420 --> 00:45:15.070
for kind of seeing where you go
and what shops and restaurants

00:45:15.070 --> 00:45:15.890
you like to visit.

00:45:15.890 --> 00:45:18.815
Do you have any other kind
of guides to Paris online?

00:45:18.815 --> 00:45:19.690
DORIE GREENSPAN: Yes.

00:45:19.690 --> 00:45:23.720
OK, so I think you should
look at a website called

00:45:23.720 --> 00:45:25.180
parisbymouth.com.

00:45:25.180 --> 00:45:27.110
Do you know it?

00:45:27.110 --> 00:45:29.150
Oh, I see a nod over there.

00:45:29.150 --> 00:45:29.770
Yeah.

00:45:29.770 --> 00:45:33.580
Yeah, it's a great site
for-- it's a food site.

00:45:33.580 --> 00:45:36.160
It's a great site for
restaurants, for pastry shops,

00:45:36.160 --> 00:45:38.230
for bakeries.

00:45:38.230 --> 00:45:41.420
They also do tours.

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:44.820
So I've taken the cheese
tour and learned so much.

00:45:44.820 --> 00:45:45.400
It's great.

00:45:45.400 --> 00:45:47.910
They do a cheese tour,
they do wine tastings.

00:45:47.910 --> 00:45:52.861
Yes, it's a friend who started
it, but it's a great site

00:45:52.861 --> 00:45:53.860
and it's all in English.

00:45:53.860 --> 00:45:55.730
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
David Lebovitz's site?

00:45:55.730 --> 00:45:57.938
DORIE GREENSPAN: Yes, David
Lebovitz's site is great.

00:45:57.938 --> 00:46:02.770
It's David L-E-B-O-V-I-T-Z.
And Alec Lobrano,

00:46:02.770 --> 00:46:05.780
or Alexander Lobrano's
site, particularly his

00:46:05.780 --> 00:46:11.170
Diner's Diary-- also good.

00:46:11.170 --> 00:46:13.480
MALE SPEAKER: I guess on the
subject of David Lebovitz,

00:46:13.480 --> 00:46:15.420
we had him here
earlier in the year

00:46:15.420 --> 00:46:17.630
and so it seems like
you two know each other.

00:46:17.630 --> 00:46:20.500
Are there bake-offs or
collaborations or things

00:46:20.500 --> 00:46:21.010
like that?

00:46:21.010 --> 00:46:22.510
DORIE GREENSPAN:
No, no, no, no, no.

00:46:22.510 --> 00:46:24.440
They're a happy going
out to eat together.

00:46:24.440 --> 00:46:24.940
Yeah.

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:25.320
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:26.903
DORIE GREENSPAN:
Yeah, no competition.

00:46:26.903 --> 00:46:27.920
MALE SPEAKER: Awesome.

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:30.940
And also how do you test the
recipes in your cookbook?

00:46:30.940 --> 00:46:31.750
Is there a--

00:46:31.750 --> 00:46:32.640
DORIE GREENSPAN: Oh,
that's a great question.

00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:32.890
MALE SPEAKER: --trusted tester?

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:33.806
DORIE GREENSPAN: Yeah.

00:46:33.806 --> 00:46:38.600
So all of these recipes were
either gathered, begged,

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:42.710
groveled for in Paris
or created in Paris

00:46:42.710 --> 00:46:46.530
and then they were all tested,
tested, tested, retested,

00:46:46.530 --> 00:46:50.010
retested in America with
American ingredients.

00:46:50.010 --> 00:46:52.460
So the two ingredients
that are hardest

00:46:52.460 --> 00:46:57.430
to kind of translate
from France to America

00:46:57.430 --> 00:46:58.860
are flour and butter.

00:46:58.860 --> 00:47:02.250
Because the flour is
weaker in France, and so

00:47:02.250 --> 00:47:05.550
in some instances I had to
use less flour in a recipe,

00:47:05.550 --> 00:47:09.960
and the butter is richer
in France than it is here.

00:47:09.960 --> 00:47:12.600
And so all of the
recipes were tested here.

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:17.200
I worked with Mary Dodd,
who was my recipe tester.

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:20.480
And by the time I would
give Mary a recipe,

00:47:20.480 --> 00:47:23.630
I had worked on it
and worked on it

00:47:23.630 --> 00:47:25.170
until I thought
it was just right.

00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:29.240
So I didn't send her things
that had holes in them.

00:47:29.240 --> 00:47:31.720
And I would send them
to her fully written

00:47:31.720 --> 00:47:35.930
so that she could test the
actual formula, the ingredients

00:47:35.930 --> 00:47:37.790
and test the writing.

00:47:37.790 --> 00:47:39.750
You know-- do the
directions make sense?

00:47:39.750 --> 00:47:43.630
Because after-- if I've created
a recipe, if I've made it

00:47:43.630 --> 00:47:46.780
several times, you know I
can take some things for

00:47:46.780 --> 00:47:52.700
granted that-- so
everybody needs an editor.

00:47:52.700 --> 00:47:55.580
And so it was really good that
she could read them and say,

00:47:55.580 --> 00:47:59.360
do you think people will
really know-- and point out

00:47:59.360 --> 00:48:00.080
things like that.

00:48:00.080 --> 00:48:03.030
So she tested everything
and we tested the recipes

00:48:03.030 --> 00:48:06.330
with volume measures--
cups and spoons--

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:08.190
and also with metric measures.

00:48:08.190 --> 00:48:13.770
And I'm thrilled, I am so happy,
to have metric in the book.

00:48:13.770 --> 00:48:18.569
It's the first time my publisher
has said yes so I'm happy.

00:48:18.569 --> 00:48:19.360
MALE SPEAKER: Cool.

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:24.460
Any final questions to see
us on to the book signing?

00:48:24.460 --> 00:48:27.650
I'll end with another one--
the photos are so beautiful.

00:48:27.650 --> 00:48:29.882
Do you use the same
photographer with each book?

00:48:29.882 --> 00:48:31.590
How do you approach
the food photography?

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:33.048
DORIE GREENSPAN:
So the photography

00:48:33.048 --> 00:48:36.780
for my last three books,
"Baking From My Home to Yours,"

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:39.390
"Around My French Table,"
and "Baking Chez Moi,"

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:40.500
it's the same team.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:44.430
So it's Alan Richardson
who does the photography,

00:48:44.430 --> 00:48:46.790
Karen Tack does
the food styling,

00:48:46.790 --> 00:48:48.390
Deb Donahue does the props.

00:48:48.390 --> 00:48:51.750
But Alan and Karen wrote
books you might know-- "Hello,

00:48:51.750 --> 00:48:56.780
Cupcake"-- yeah,
they're the cupcakers--

00:48:56.780 --> 00:49:01.657
"What's New Cupcake-- and
yeah, so it's the same team.

00:49:01.657 --> 00:49:02.740
MALE SPEAKER: Cool, great.

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:04.280
DORIE GREENSPAN: They're
great to work with.

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:05.060
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:06.434
Well, on this
Googleween, we were

00:49:06.434 --> 00:49:09.810
supremely happy to have a salute
to the French baked goods,

00:49:09.810 --> 00:49:12.340
so thank you very much for
speaking with us, Dorie, and--

00:49:12.340 --> 00:49:13.150
DORIE GREENSPAN:
Thank you, Cliff.

00:49:13.150 --> 00:49:14.390
Thank you all for coming.

00:49:14.390 --> 00:49:14.990
Thank you.

